## assign this to a short name for convenience
hg19 <- BSgenome.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg19

# Create an empty character vector to store the concatenated sequences
seqvec <- character(nrow(data_edit))

# Loop through each row of data_edit and concatenate the sequences
for (i in 1:nrow(data_edit)) {
  getseqrow <- data_edit[i,]
  dnaseq <- getSeq(x = hg19, names = getseqrow$chr, start = getseqrow$start, end = getseqrow$end)
  # Ensure dnaseq is not a list
  dnaseq <- as.character(dnaseq)
  # Concatenate sequences with a separator
  seqvec[i] <- paste(dnaseq, collapse = "")
}

# Add the concatenated sequences as a new column in data_edit
data_edit$exonseq <- seqvec

Obtain strand information for the sequences

a. Obtain strand information based on gene names

# Load the biomaRt package
library(biomaRt)

# Specify the Ensembl Grch37/hg19
ensembl = useMart("ENSEMBL_MART_ENSEMBL",dataset="hsapiens_gene_ensembl",host="https://grch37.ensembl.org")
#get all unique gene symbols from the dataset
unique_genes <- unique(data_edit$gene_symbol)

# Query Ensembl once for all gene symbols
genestrand <- getBM(
  attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "strand", "external_gene_name"),
  filters = "external_gene_name",
  values = unique_genes,
  mart = ensembl
)

#merge the data back with the original data
data_with_strand <- merge(data_edit, genestrand, by.x = "gene_symbol", by.y = "external_gene_name")
#remove duplicated rows based on gene names before merging with master table "finaldata"
data_with_strand_rm <- data_with_strand %>%
  mutate(tmp_id = paste(gene_symbol, chr, start, end, sep = "_")) %>%  
  distinct(tmp_id, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%                               
  select(-tmp_id)
#Since not all strand information can be found using gene name, we also look for strand information using chromosomal location
#create a copy of data_edit since we need to modify the chr column
data_edit_2<-data_edit

#remove chr from chr column as the biomaRt strand location can only retrieve from chromosome number without "chr"
data_edit_2$chr<-gsub('chr','',data_edit_2$chr)
data_edit_2$chr <- as.integer(data_edit_2$chr)

b. Because strand information is not always available through gene names, obtain it using chromosomal location as well.


#get strand info of the sequences based on chromosomal location instead of gene name
genestrand_chr <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:nrow(data_edit_2)) {
  getseqrow <- data_edit_2[i,]
  
  # Create a chromosomal region string like "7:140424943:140624564"
  region <- paste0(getseqrow$chr, ":", getseqrow$start, ":", getseqrow$end)
  
  # Query BioMart using chromosomal_region filter
  gene_info_chr <- getBM(
    attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id", "strand", "external_gene_name"),
    filters = "chromosomal_region",
    values = region,
    mart = ensembl
  )
  
  genestrand_chr <- rbind(genestrand_chr, gene_info_chr)
}

#remove duplicated rows based on gene names
genestrand_chr_rm <- genestrand_chr[!duplicated(genestrand_chr$external_gene_name), ]

#check data
genestrand_chr_rm

#remove duplicated rows based on gene names

#check data

#merge the two "strand" columns 
#Replace NA values in column "strand" where there is a non-NA value in the corresponding row of the second dataframe
finaldata$strand.x[is.na(finaldata$strand.x) & !is.na(finaldata$strand.y)] <- finaldata$strand.y[is.na(finaldata$strand.x) & !is.na(finaldata$strand.y)]

#Drop the extra columns strand.y
finaldata <- finaldata[, !(names(finaldata) %in% c("strand.y"))]

# rename strand.x to A
names(finaldata)[names(finaldata) == "strand.x"] <- "strand"

#check data
finaldata

Reverse-complement the sequences if they are on the reverse strand

#in a new column "rcseq", if the strand is reverse then reverse complement the sequences, if not keep the original sequences
library(Biostrings)
finaldata$rcseq<-ifelse(finaldata$strand == "-1",
                     reverseComplement(DNAStringSet(finaldata$exonseq)),
                     finaldata$exonseq)

# Extract last 3 bases from column rcseq into new column to identify motifs
finaldata$lastthreebases <- substr(finaldata$rcseq, nchar(finaldata$rcseq) - 2, nchar(finaldata$rcseq))

# Replace "t" with "U" in the column since it is RNA sequences
finaldata$lastthreebases <- gsub("T", "U", finaldata$lastthreebases)

Identify sequence motifs and visualize them

library(seqLogo)


brana<-dplyr::filter(finaldata,finaldata$drug=="Branaplam")

# Filter rows with sequences containing exactly 3 bases
brana_three <- brana %>% dplyr::filter(nchar(lastthreebases) == 3)


# Function to create position weight matrix
create_pwm <- function(sequences) {
  # Initialize an empty matrix to store the counts
  pwm <- matrix(0, nrow = 4, ncol = nchar(sequences[[1]]),
                dimnames = list(c("A", "C", "G", "U"), 1:nchar(sequences[[1]])))

  # Loop through each sequence
  for (seq in sequences) {
    # Split the sequence into individual nucleotides
    nucleotides <- strsplit(seq, "")[[1]]
    # Count the occurrences of each nucleotide at each position
    for (i in 1:length(nucleotides)) {
      pwm[nucleotides[i], i] <- pwm[nucleotides[i], i] + 1
    }
  }

  # Normalize the counts to frequencies
  pwm <- pwm / colSums(pwm)

  return(pwm)
}

# Create PWM from the sequences in df$column
pwm <- create_pwm(brana_three$lastthreebases)
p <- makePWM(pwm)
seqLogo(p,ic.scale=FALSE)
